gomodel:SYNGO_3597  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: 14/5/2018 Pim\nrule: NAS_CPLX_2\nrationale: Polyribosomes are present in dendritic spines (PMID:12165474, electron microscopy). The ribosome is the central holoenzyme in the process of \"translation (GO:0006412)\". RL11 is a generally accepted constituent of the ribosome that together with other ribosomal subunits contributes to the intrinsic activity of the ribosomal complex.. No functions of RL11 are known independent from the ribosomal complex. Inference to term \"translation (GO:0006412)\" occurs_in \"postsynapse (GO:0098794:)\" is trivial.\nC_ref CC: PMID:12165474 (dendritic spine head)\nP_inf CC: SynGO ID #620\nP_inf CC additional:\n- Bayes et al.(2012), PMID:23071613, TableS1, prep:psd\n- Collins et al.(2006), PMID:16635246, consensus, prep:psd\n- Distler et al.(2014), PMID:25211037, Table S1, prep:synapse\nComplex membership: RL10 protein is a fixed member of the 60S ribosomal subunit complex.\n- Shown in crystal structure (PMID:28138070, see Fig.1, name: ul5)\n- GO annotations to \"structural constituent of ribosome (GO:0003735)\" (ISO and IEA). Experimental description: \"PSD fractions were prepared from rat forebrains largely as previously described (4, 9).\" p. 21004\n\n8/8/2017 Pim\n- Proteomics database search returned human RL11 protein, but this is a problem with the data base search configuration." ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-0269-0311" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-9880-1214" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0001-9377-7414" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-9681-3318" ;
        dc:date           "2018-05-23" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_3597" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_10116" .

